My visual data story

Daily Interaction Pattern Logging at UoA

Introduction

This visual data story explores daily interaction patterns across various UoA City Campus spaces. The data collected provides insights into the frequency, type, and group size of interactions observed in shared areas.

Interaction Density by Time of Day

The following visualization highlights the density of interactions across different periods of the day, allowing us to identify peak times for group and individual interactions.

Density Plot

The density plot provides a clear visualization of interaction patterns across different periods of the day. The analysis reveals distinct peaks in interaction density during the afternoon (12pm-4pm) and evening (4pm-8pm), indicating that these are the most active periods for social and study interactions at UoA. The late morning (9am-12pm) also exhibits moderate interaction density, suggesting that mid-morning is another common time for group or individual interactions. Conversely, the early morning (6am-9am) and night (8pm-12am) display significantly lower interaction densities, indicating fewer logged observations during these hours. This information can help in understanding peak periods for campus activities and resource usage.

Device Usage by Interaction Type

This bar plot compares the frequency of different interaction type patterns against the proportion of device use, highlighting which interactions types have devices being more prevalent.

Bar Plot

The bar plot effectively compares interaction types against device usage, revealing key insights into how technology is integrated into different social contexts. Eating/Drinking and Socializing (including sports/gym) interactions exhibit higher counts of interactions without device usage, highlighting a more face-to-face interaction pattern in these contexts. In contrast, Individual Study and Individual Timepass/Couple Socializing show higher instances of device use, indicating that solitary or semi-private interactions are more likely to involve mobile devices or laptops. The Waiting interaction type also shows a significant device usage, suggesting that idle time is frequently filled with mobile interaction. These insights can guide targeted campus policies related to digital engagement and study space design.

Distribution of Interactions by Location

The boxplot below visualizes the distribution of interaction counts across key UoA City Campus areas, emphasizing spaces with higher and lower interaction density.

Boxplot

The boxplot visualizes the distribution of group sizes across various areas on campus, revealing notable spatial differences in interaction patterns. Lecture/Tutorial/Seminar/Workshop Spaces exhibit the widest range of group sizes, indicating that these areas are highly variable in terms of crowd density. Smaller group interactions are more common in Cafeteria/Eateries, Library/IT Space, and Lounge/Sofa Spaces, suggesting that these spaces are more conducive to small group study or casual socializing. The Bus Stop and Gym areas show minimal variation in group size, implying more uniform interaction patterns in these spaces. These spatial insights can inform campus planning to optimize space allocation for different group sizes and activities.

Conclusion

The visual data analysis of interaction patterns across different periods, contexts, and areas at the University of Auckland provides key insights into how social and study spaces are utilized on campus. The density plot indicates that afternoon and evening periods are the most interaction-dense, suggesting peak hours for social and academic engagements. The bar plot reveals that device usage is most prevalent in individual and semi-private contexts, highlighting a potential area for digital engagement strategies. Finally, the boxplot emphasizes the variability of group sizes across different spaces, particularly in lecture and seminar areas. These findings offer a comprehensive overview of how students commonly interact in shared spaces, guiding potential recommendations for campus planning, resource allocation, and targeted digital initiatives.
